Simple ways to help your child deal with anger.
I often find that the parents view a child's display of anger and resentment as wrong and abnormal.
When a child expresses his anger openly, we do not know how to react, says psychologist Ekaterina Kess.
The specialist encourages a small discussion about these natural and human emotions - the anger and resentment that everyone experiences from time to time.
Aggression is a physical act directed at another person, and it usually occurs when we feel angry.
When we adults are angry, upset, we usually know what's happening to us and how to deal with it.
We can express, suppress, conceal, keep, tell our friends or other relatives, blow up a couch in anger, smoke cigarettes (not the best way to calm our anger!), shower, put a head covering over our neck, and do other things we normally do not do.
We don't turn our aggression on others because we know different ways to deal with these emotions.
When anger is felt, children do not know what is happening to them, what to call it, or how to deal with it.
They can say, "Get out!" You're a fool!" "You're a bad mother!" "I don't want to see you!" "I'm not going to deal with you!" And very rarely can they say, "I'm mad at you".
Children literally live, they are fully present right here, right now, they are spontaneous and real in their expression of feelings, and they are often also in the grip of various emotions.
It is vital that parents do not deny, shame, or reproach their children for expressing their feelings, including anger, but, on the contrary, help them.
