German researchers are debating the number of victims of the Berlin Wall.
A new study suggests that the death toll at the former East Germany border in the Communist zone may be much higher than previously thought, but doubts remain about the true number of victims.
According to data released Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum at Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989 the West German Communist authorities abducted 1,841 people at the border with the Western Socialist Zone and later the West German Communist authorities who tried to escape from the territory they controlled.
The museum has been investigating border-related deaths for years, and it's adjusting the death toll every now and then.
This year, 11 more deaths have been reported, including a six-year-old boy who drowned while his family was trying to reach West Germany through what was then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall were Soviet army deserters.
"The full extent of the damage caused by the double evil of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented", admits museum director Alexandra Hildebrante.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to flee from a Communist-controlled state are collected and preserved", emphasized Hildebrandt in a statement circulated by the newspaper.
However, other researchers have questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is inconclusive", says Johannes Staat, an expert on East German history at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the Süddeutsche Zeitung.
He and other researchers at the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have only been able to confirm 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that 138 people were killed by the Communists at the Berlin Wall alone.
Given the number of people who have died trying to escape across the Baltic Sea or to reach the West through neighbouring territories, the State estimates the number of victims could be as high as 1,000.
But it's still significantly less than 1841.
One reason for the different casualty numbers could be due to different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie Museum also records all suicides of East Germany border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also records deaths that are not directly related to violence.
"If seniors in their 70s and 80s die of heart attacks after crossing the border", Hildebrante says, "it must be the result of this 'cold border'.
However, the State is convinced that a distinction must be made between the elderly who may have died as a result of their experience of wandering and those whose deaths were caused by prolonged waiting in the hot hours on a bus at the border.
Regardless, it is not easy to count the victims, since the Communist authorities in East-Hungary did not record such statistics, and researchers have to dig up documents in various scattered archives, the State says.
However, the State Group has recently acquired new documents and may therefore issue a new estimate of the number of victims in the near future.
