A French court has rejected a request to tear down the shops in the Jungle refugee camp.
A French court has rejected a request by authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of self-made shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, home to several thousand refugees.
At a court hearing in Calais this week, the authorities said the state should demolish 72 self-made shops where people sell various goods such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer hairdressing, 50 cents (40p) tea and simple meals for a few euros in self-made restaurants.
The prefect's office in Kalua stated that these self-created enterprises should be demolished because they constitute a shadow economy and do not pay taxes, as well as pose fire and sanitary risks.
Representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small enterprises are important because the food supplied by the government and the support groups does not meet the needs of the camp, where the number of inhabitants continues to grow.
They also pointed out that home-made shops and restaurants often offer free accommodation and food to those who need it most.
The Lille Court has ruled that there is no legal basis to expel people who have set up 72 self-made shops, but that understands the concerns of the prefect of Calais.
Justice Jean-François Molla said that food, coffee, and restaurants play a greater role than simply providing food for people living in "extremely poor conditions".
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meeting places for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places at risk of being displaced is the camp's café, Jungle Book Kids, which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French classes, and provides asylum counseling to hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children's coffee shop.
A letter to the Guardian said that the closure of the cafe "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are as young as eight".
On Friday, two charities, Refugee Aid and L'Auberge des Migrants, reported that the number of people living in the Jungle camp had risen to 9,000, the highest since the summer's influx of migrants.
