In Spain, the possibility of reducing the budget deficit was not threatened by the possibility of forming a government.
On 12 July the European Commission (EC) concluded that Spain and Portugal had not implemented sufficient measures to reduce the budget deficit to the 3% of GDP required by the euro area.
Estimates show that despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's budget deficit stood at 4,4% of GDP at the end of last year, compared with 5,1% in Spain.
The European Commission has, however, decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while setting fiscal targets for the near term.
One of the reasons why the EC has not yet imposed sanctions on both countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many EU countries.
Additional sanctions would only increase such negative sentiment.
Critics point out that the EC is inconsistent in its decisions, agreeing on uniform rules from the outset and then failing to apply them in practice.
For example, the President of the German Bundesbank, Jens Veidmann, has pointed out that Europe is losing confidence in itself by creating the impression among citizens that EU rules are advisory rather than binding.
The Commission has now proposed and all Member States have approved an extension of the deadline for the budget deficit to the end of this year for Portugal and to 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission intends to review the progress made by both countries in the coming months, while indicating that both Spain and Portugal must be ready to introduce further austerity measures if circumstances so require.
Initial forecasts suggest that Portugal could reach its target in time and that the budget deficit could fall to 2.5% of GDP this year.
This means that the government of that country has to implement a saving of 0,25% of GDP this year under the Stability Programme.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with additional attention to controlling the cost of purchasing goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
The budget deficit should be reduced to 4,6% of GDP this year, to 3,1% next year and to 2,2% in 2018.
In addition, consolidation measures should amount to 0,5% of GDP per year for the next two years.
