NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
Based on NASA's latest climate models, Venus was once a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Research have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms that are also used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, which has a hot surface, no water, and an atmosphere almost entirely composed of carbon, has ever experienced conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' dense atmosphere explains its slow rate of collapse.
But recent simulations suggest that Venus once had a flat, Earth-like atmosphere, and it's been slowly rotating.
The models also look at the early topography of Venus.
The planet had more dry land than Earth, but it had enough water and geographical diversity to support life and prevent water evaporation.
In the early days of Venus, the sun was 30 percent brighter.
The GISS model of the rotation of Venus shows that the bright part of the day lasts for two months, explained Antonio Del Genio, a GISS scientist, in a press release.
This process warms the planet's surface and causes matter to form thick cloud layers that act as a rain-guard, shielding the planet from the sun's heat.
The result is a temperate climate, which is actually several degrees below the temperature of the earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, which is similar to the theory of evolution that scientists have hypothesized.
Although once habitable, Venus has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light for billions of years.
The oceans were boiling, and the volcanoes were being burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When the water completely evaporated, only the flat carbon dioxide atmosphere of the deadly greenhouse gas known today as Venus remained.
The scientists published the results of a new climate model for Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
