Kepler measured the rate of collapse of stars in the Pleiades star.
The new Kepler mission has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the speed at which stars collide in the Pleiades star.
The new data help astronomers to understand why the stars in this galaxy rotate at different speeds and how the rate of star collapse is related to the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with those of other stars, we will gain a deeper understanding of the relationship between the mass of stars, their age, and even the history of the solar system", said Louise Rebula, a scientist at Caltech's Infrared Process and Analysis Center in Pasadena, California, in a news release.
The Pleiades star is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this galaxy are just beginning to grow, reaching about 125 million years of age.
They're spinning at full speed.
At their maximum speed, these growing stars emit a large amount of stellar wind.
When the worms enter the magnetic field of the star, they slow down the star.
As stars age, their rate of collapse decreases.
Kepler measures the rate of each star's collapse by determining the time between the appearance of a recognizable star region, such as a solar eclipse.
The latest catalog of stellar rotation rates shows that larger stars rotate slower than smaller stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, and the larger dancers are doing their pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
Rebull says that in the Pleiades "ballet", slow-spinning objects are larger and more massive, while fast-spinning objects are very small stars.
Because of its proximity, Pleiades serves as a great space laboratory where we can compare the properties of stars with their rotational velocities.
Rebull says that the Pleiades star helps to build theoretical models of the rotation of stars in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have much to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down and stop completely.
Rebull and his colleagues have detailed their analysis of the rate of collapse of the stars of Pleiades in three new publications that will soon be published in the Journal of Astronomy.
